VP. SURYA RAOIn connection with the 124th Jayanthi of the legendary vocal vidwan,  Late Parupalli Ramakrishnaiah Pantulu, Gayakasarvabhowma Sangeeta Parishat presented a five-day musical feast at Sri Sivaramakrishna Kshetram, Vijayawada. T. Swathi Srikrishna of Chennai gave the first concert on the inaugural day. Swathi, a disciple of late Krishnamacharyulu and a competent singer, started her concert withSahana varnamand followed it withRaghunayakainHamsadhvani,at the end of which she impressed with finekalpana swaras.Mayamalavagowlawas explicitly elaborated and thekritiMerusamanaalso carried goodswaras. ThoughNanupalimpainMohanawas the major item of the concert, Swathi excelled in the delineation ofVaraliin which she renderedBangaru Kamakshi. TheMohanaelaboration came out as a fine essay of theraga bhava. Swathi had fine support from B. V. Durgabhavani (violin) and K. Sadguracharan (mridangam).From the second day onwards the programme started with junior concerts. Smt. Rama Bhagawan sang a rare composition of DikshitarSri GanesatparaminVeenavadiniand presented a splendidKambhojipreceeding thekritiMarakatavalli. Rama was accompanied by G. Seetaramalakshmi on the violin and K. Sai Giridhar on the mridangam.The main concert of the evening was a  vocal duet by  Malladi brothers, Sriramprasad and Ravikumar. The highly gifted brothers kept the packed audience in raptures throughout with their well-blended voices, traditional style and sharpmanodharmam. The starting item was the efficiently renderedViriboniand Kalayami Raghuramam, a rare kriti of Swathi Thirunal, in Begada followed it. Theragadelineation andswarasstood as ample proof of themanodharmamability of the Malladis.The main itemChakkani Raja Margamu, the majestic composition of Thyagaraja inKharaharapriya, was memorably rendered by Prasad and Ravi with soul-stirringragadelineation and well-coordinatedkalpana swaras. Seasoned accompanists Ampolu Muralikrishna (violin) and M. Lakshminarayana Raju (mridangam) proved their mettle in their solos. The closing items of the concert wereTarangaminBilahari, a Ramadaskirtanatuned by their guru Nedunuri and a bhajan.The first programme on the third day was a vocal concert by Vemuri Viswanath, an aspiring and talented singer. His renditions ofNavaragamalika varnam,Mahaganapathim(Nata),Kamakshi,swarajathiof Syamasastri, and as the main item, Dr. Balamurali's compositionSada tavapada SannidhiminShanmukhapriya, and the RamadaskirtanaEntapanijesitivi Ramawere appealing. Viswanath was accompanied by G. Satish Babu on the violin and Sai Giridhar on the mridangam. The main programme was an instrumental ensemble comprising of D. Srinivas (veena), Surya Deepti (violin), M. L. N. Raju (mridangam) and M. Haribabu (ghatam). The group played with excellent coordination.Bottom Template Starts
